Taylor,
Attached is a draft of the complaint. I also thought I would provide you with the case cite supporting the notion of no
harm/no foul. Here you go:
Where a party to a contract, without any legal justification, breaches the contract, the non-breaching party is
entitled to recover, at least, nominal damages, if no other damages are proven. See, e.g., Hoag v. Jenan, 86
Cal.App.2d, 556, 563, 195 P.2d 451 (1948).
[***]
[T]he rule is that, where a right of a plaintiff is established, failure to show actual or substantial damages will
not defeat recovery, but a judgment for nominal damages will be entered.
Am.Jur.2d Damages § 10.
I have been trying to track down the PA. Law Encyclopedia citation I gave you a while back, but the PL LE is no
longer online. Let me know if you have questions about anything. I will leave it with, but may tinker with the
damages section.
